Is it possible to regulate systemic risks?
MILAN – Over the past two years, the global economy has been hit hard by financial instability and sudden shifts in market dynamics.
Such events are likely to occur again because, as we emerge from the crisis, the global economy remains imbalanced in many ways, particularly concerning sovereign debts and the structure of global demand.
Systemic risks are at the root of most crises and present challenges for several reasons.
Firstly, they are not easy to detect with certainty and even more difficult to prove.
Next, predicting the exact moment of the breaking point (when bubbles burst, when markets are paralyzed, and when credit is no longer available) is, and will likely remain, beyond our analytical capabilities.
Finally, crises are highly nonlinear events that occur without warning signs.
The periodic manifestations of instability impose a high social cost on those least responsible for them.
If this pattern were to repeat itself, it could erode confidence in financial markets and regulatory authorities, a loss of confidence that could lead to excessive regulation, state takeover, and disengagement from globalization.
But the problem is even more serious.
The financial and economic crisis is transforming into a sovereign debt crisis for advanced countries.
Economic and financial imbalances can lead to dangerous fiscal imbalances characterized by deteriorating tax revenues and increased bailout spending.
The International Monetary Fund estimates that up to 75 percent of the "fiscal packages" in advanced economies include non-discretionary countercyclical measures.
The imbalances and undetected systemic risks mean that what appear to be prudent fiscal policies are in fact not.
For example, Spain did not have a fiscal deficit at the start of the crisis.
But its revenues and expenditures were largely determined by a housing bubble linked to very high debt.
An extreme fiscal imbalance can also lead to a "growth trap" in which fiscal consolidation has such a negative effect on growth that it cancels itself out.
Greece is likely a prime example of this.
In the end, the only way out is to reset the value of liabilities through restructuring or inflation.
If systemic risks can cause this kind of sequential imbalance in cascades, sovereign states must be vigilant about the danger, capable of identifying the emergence of a systemic risk, and quick to take corrective measures.
New detailed legislative frameworks, focusing on capital requirements and leverage effects, transparency, ratings, and other sources of information, incentives, conflicts of interest, and limits on the size of financial institutions, consumer protection, and resolution mechanisms will soon be adopted.
The hope is that these reforms will reduce the likelihood and severity of systemic risks.
But this will do nothing to address the problem of global imbalances and other factors contributing to and signaling instability.
In addition and complementing new legislative frameworks, a comprehensive system for monitoring systemic risks is necessary.
However, some politicians and leading analysts argue that such a system, aimed at identifying and mitigating systemic risks, is futile.
The incomplete models of risk dynamics and a complex and constantly evolving global financial system make it, according to them, either impossible or so error-prone that such efforts would be futile.
Asset bubbles are almost impossible to identify without error.
If skeptics are right, we must then accept that we will periodically find ourselves in a situation of financial and fiscal instability that we cannot predict in advance.
We should also then accept a much more prudent fiscal policy than we deemed necessary just three years ago.
In the realm of statistics and decision-making under uncertainty, errors are inevitable.
There are two types of errors: one is rejecting a true proposal, and the other is accepting a false one.
Let's call them RQV (rejected when true) and AQF (accepted when false).
The question can be framed as follows: in the context of detecting and responding to systemic risks, which of these two types of errors has the highest likely cost?
Opponents of prudent risk monitoring hold two different positions.
One of them is that the AQF error will not occur because there is no reliable sign heralding an increasing potential instability.
Seeking such a sign is a waste of time.
Instability occurs instantly.
But this position seems fallacious.
For example, during the 2008 crisis, some analysts issued warnings and some investors took notice.
However, it must be admitted that these warnings may not have been sufficient to be irrefutable and they certainly did not predict the breaking point.
They were nevertheless undeniable signs.
The second viewpoint is that there are indeed warning signs, but they are so unreliable that taking measures would do more harm than good.
This perspective implies that AQF has a higher likely cost than RQV, because there are many false positive elements and/or that the remedy is worse than the problem.
There is no doubt that there are costs associated with AQF errors.
But RQV is also costly, as we have seen, so the aggregate negative effect of a reaction to false positives (AQF) must be significant to be convincing.
I am not convinced, however.
There may be a deeper trend at play.
Whether in business or investments, choices are constantly made under conditions of uncertainty, and errors are frequent.
The default position of advanced country decision-makers seems to be, instead, that proactive and preemptive measures require a high level of certainty, linked to the deeply ingrained belief that financial markets are stable and self-regulate.
If one believes that market instability is rare, it is then reasonable to refuse to act unless there are good reasons to do so.
But in light of past experiences, the idea that the global financial system is only exceptionally unstable or on a slippery slope is at the very least questionable.
Based on new theories and experiences, we might eventually conclude that political responses to systemic risks are impossible to develop and that the cost of AQR errors is higher than the cost of QRV errors.
But we should at least try this approach, and in doing so, assign responsibilities to a new institution, or an existing one, that has access to relevant information, possesses sharp analytical skills at both financial and macroeconomic levels, and is relatively insulated from conflicts of interest.
Its analysis should be made public and could thus influence perceptions of systemic risks and market behavior, thereby increasing the system's ability to self-regulate.
